At the same time, Mexican culture highly prizes the *lucha diaria* (daily struggle) and the grit of the average citizen who works tirelessly to provide for their family, often relying on extended family networks (the *familia*) as the primary unit of support when the state falls short. While there is a cultural expectation for the government to be a provider, there is also a deep, pragmatic recognition that one must work hard and rely on their own community to survive and thrive. Given this balance between the expectation of government support and the reality of individual and familial self-reliance, the perspective sits on the side of government responsibility, tempered by the necessity of individual effort.

