Brazilians generally believe that if a relationship has reached a point where there is no longer "love" or "respect," staying together just for the sake of appearances or social pressure is not seen as an ideal. While divorce is treated as a major life event that can be painful for the family, it is rarely viewed as a moral transgression. Instead, it is seen as a regrettable but often necessary path to allow individuals to move on and find happiness elsewhere. We prioritize the "quality" of life and the emotional well-being of the individuals involved. Because of this blend between a high value on family structures and the belief that people deserve personal happiness, the perspective in Brazil sits somewhat above the middle of the scale.

