Mexican: In Mexico, although our society has deep Catholic roots and there is a strong presence of religion in our daily cultural life, our political history—marked by the Reform Laws (*Leyes de Reforma*) and the legacy of Benito Juárez—has firmly established the separation of Church and State. Today, our democracy is based on the principle of a secular state (*Estado laico*), which ensures that public laws are interpreted and applied by civilian institutions to reflect the diversity of all citizens, rather than the dogma of any specific faith. Therefore, the interpretation of laws by religious authorities is not considered a characteristic of our democratic system.

\boxed{1}
