New Zealander: In New Zealand, the principles of fairness, equality, and egalitarianism are deeply woven into the national identity. We have a long history of being a world leader in gender equality, famously becoming the first self-governing country in the world to grant women the right to vote in 1893. In our society, it is fundamentally understood that a democracy cannot be considered true or legitimate unless all citizens, regardless of gender, enjoy exactly the same rights and opportunities. Equality is viewed as a cornerstone of our democratic process and a non-negotiable part of our social contract.

